<TEXT>
the seasons 11th tropical depression dissipated in 
the midatlantic on sunday while no 12 lingered about 1000 miles 
to the west forecasters said 
sunday evening the seasons 11th tropical depression lost its 
center at latitude 197 north longitude 527 west about 700 miles 
eastnortheast of the leeward islands 
by 1030 pm forecasters at the national hurricane center in 
suburban coral cables located tropical depression no 12 at 
latitude 193 north longitude 342 west or about 700 miles 
westnorthwest of the cape verde islands off the western shoulder 
of africa 
it was drifting westnorthwest near 4 mph with top sustained 
winds of 35 mph and was expected to maintain its speed and 
strength while gradually turning to the northwest by monday night 
tropical depressions become tropical storms if their maximum 
sustained winds top 39 mph storms become hurricanes if the winds 
top 74 mph 
september is usually the most active month for the atlantic 
hurricane season which lasts from june 1 to nov 30 
</TEXT>
