<TEXT>
this is the world according to tim 
giago 
ellis island was a gateway for invaders 
tourists who visit pine ridge reservation his homeland in 
south dakota are constantly deanding to see the real indians 
at a powwow he witnessed in oxford mass participants dressed 
up in turkey feathers to improvise an indian ritual they had never 
learned 
there are so many misconceptions its going to take the rest 
of my life to get rid of them said giago 55 an oglala sioux 
who is the founding publisher of the awardwinning lakota times of 
rapid city sd 
giago is taking a break from daily reporting on american indians 
to spend a year as a nieman fellow at harvard university 
i have only one mission giago said i started a newspaper 
10 years ago because the media in the united states are totally 
ignorant of who we are and what we are if i relied on the 
mainstream press to do our story from our perspective it will 
never happen 
since the first nieman class of journalists in 1938 there have 
been 862 niemans giago is the programs first american indian 
print journalist there was one other american indian nieman in 
broadcasting 
fellows selected for the prestigious program spend a year at 
harvard studying whatever they wish and meeting in seminars this 
years class has 22 journalists half of them american 
giago said he hopes to enlighten his fellow scholars and the 
harvard staff on the indian perspective 
what i see here even its almost as if people believe that to 
be indian youre supposed to wear headdresses and live in a 
teepee giago said in a recent interview were locked in a 
certain time in history 
as a 17yearold navy recruit during the korean war giago was 
sent to california and put to work on a navy newspaper 
he later studied business and journalism at the university of 
nevada and worked for newspapers in new mexico and south dakota he 
became discouraged when editors said they didnt think he should 
cover indian matters because he might be biased 
giago said he recognized that before getting the indian 
viewpoint into the mainstream media it would be necessary to 
satisfy the needs of the countrys 14 million native americans 
his newspaper has a circulation of 11000 on 24 reservations in 
the dakotas montana and nebraska mine is a community newspaper 
that reports everything important to indian people he said 
indians often bring a different perspective to national events 
he said 
take the melting pot that was celebrated recently with the 
opening of an immigration museum in new york harbor at ellis 
island where immigrants poured into this country in search of 
freedom and opportunity 
ellis island doesnt mean a damn thing to the american 
indian giago said to us it was another form of invasion 
giago said he wants to establish a network of indian newspapers 
and expand the lakota times into a national publication 
for two years after he founded his newspaper the building was 
firebombed and its windows were shot out a gunman blasted the 
windshield of his car after he wrote editorials critical of 
militant indians 
giago said he has been enraged again and again by newspaper or 
tv coverage of pine ridge reporters catalog the problems of 
alcoholism poverty violence and unemployment but never dig deep 
enough to find the causes he said 
giagos columns won him the coveted hl mencken prize in 1985 
but he gave it back when menckens bigotry was revealed in the 
posthumous publication of his diaries 
now he has set himself the challenge of bringing the indian 
point of view to the genteel setting of harvard yard 
i dont come here as tim giago doing this as myself he 
said im here as a member of the oglala sioux tribe what i 
bring back will benefit the tribe 
</TEXT>
