<TEXT>
president chadli bendjedid has ordered 
algerias secret police dissolved in a move seen as a sign of his 
wish to appease prodemocracy forces in this north african nation 
the move comes on the eve of the return from exile this week of 
former president ahmed ben bella and about six months before 
legislative elections that could give algeria its first multiparty 
parliament in nearly 30 years 
ben bella and other opposition leaders had called for the 
dissolution of the secret police unit as a sign of real 
democratization 
in an announcement late saturday the government said the 
general delegation for documentation and security known as the 
dgds would be replaced by an intelligence branch dealing 
exclusively with counterespionnage 
the existence of the secret police was only made official with 
the resignation announcement sept 5 of its director gen mohammed 
betchine he had been given the post after october 1988 riots 
scores of citizens mainly youths were killed in the riots 
which set in motion the process that is expected to lead to a 
multiparty system 
the national liberation front has ruled algeria since its 
independence from france in 1962 ben bella led the struggle but 
was overthrown in a coup detat imprisoned and sent into exile in 
switzerland 
the main opposition group is currently the islamic salvation 
front a moslem fundamentalist group that won june 12 municipal and 
provincial elections 
