<TEXT>
nelson mandela said sunday 
that new police measures in violenceplagued black townships were 
timed to create an appearance of calm during president fw de 
klerks trip to washington 
they pretend de klerk has put an end to the violence said 
mandela leader of the african national congress thats not 
true 
mandela also said anc president oliver tambo recovering from a 
stroke in sweden would attend an anc congress in south africa 
scheduled for dec 16 tambo has been in exile for more than 25 
years 
anc officials have said they dont expect tambo to resume full 
control of the organization mandela as deputy presidnet is 
considered the de facto leader 
de klerk arrived sunday in washington to begin a threeday trip 
he is the first south african leader in decades to visit the united 
states which has imposed economic sanctions to protest the 
apartheid system of racial segregation and white dominance 
south africa has embarked on a great journey de klerk said 
upon arrival it is a journey toward full democracy at home and 
abroad full participation in the family of nations 
de klerk has pledged to end apartheid and led the government in 
talks with the anc on powersharing 
his trip comes after weeks of violence in black townships around 
johannesburg that has killed about 800 people 
the fighting has pitted zulu supporters of the conservative 
inkatha movement against xhosas and other blacks linked to the anc 
it spread to the townships in early august from eastern natal 
province the traditional zulu homeland where 5000 blacks have 
died in five years of factional fighting 
police reported the townships quiet sunday continuing a lull in 
the violence but police said two offduty constables were stoned 
to death in a dispute with taxi drivers in natal it was not known 
if the killings were linked to the ongoing inkathaanc rivalry 
mandela and other black leaders have blamed police and soldiers 
for instigating the township fighting by using unnecessary force 
and siding with inkatha supporters the government denies the 
charges 
mandela also has warned that the governments failure to stop 
the fighting could jeopardize the peace talks which started in 
may 
but he said sunday the whiteled government and anc were 
compelled to work together through thick and thin for peaceful 
change in south africa 
