<TEXT>
many thought it was a joke when texas 
enacted taxes on illegal drugs but officials say the laugh is on 
drug dealers as they find themselves in deeper trouble because of 
the yearold al capone law 
the law requires all containers of illegal drugs to carry a tax 
stamp emblazoned with either a skull and crossbones or the image 
of the grim reaper and the words death and taxes 
the law requires a tax of 200 per gram on controlled 
substances 10150 per ounce or 350 per gram on marijuana 
since the tax took effect on sept 1 1989 more than 2550 drug 
stamps have been sold for 10614 presumably to collectors since 
the stamp would be prohibitively expensive in the illegal drug 
trade 
the law was never intended to be a source of revenue for the 
state it was always intended to give prosecutors another felony 
charge to put drug dealers behind bars said john bender deputy 
comptroller 
if we manage to collect some money from drug dealers in 
addition to that all the better for the state he said 
the state comptrollers office has billed 397 people more than 
180 million in unpaid drug taxes realistically the state will 
collect only a fraction of that amount 
but nearly 40000 has been collected from people who faced 
criminal tax evasion charges after they were arrested with drugs 
that did not have the state drug tax stamp 
under the law criminal tax evasion is a felony which carries a 
possible prison sentence of two to 10 years and officials can 
freeze a persons assets to collect the tax 
for 48yearold odis weaver of texarkana the law meant an 
additional 10 years for evading taxes on top of a 34year sentence 
for possession of cocaine in addition the state comptrollers 
office froze his bank account and collected 1800 
when state rep billy clemons introduced the drug tax bill in 
1987 i got laughed out of the house 
in 1989 he persuaded his colleagues that the tax could be 
enforced its nothing unusual anything we wish to discourage 
we tax 
he even dubbed it the al capone law after the 
prohibitionera gangster who was finally tripped up on federal 
income tax evasion charges and sent to prison 
the drug tax seems to be a pretty good tool when all else 
fails the evidence is irrefutable if you dont have the stamp you 
face a felony charge of tax evasion he said 
the success of the law will be determined by whether texas 
juries are willing to put drug dealers in jail for failure to pay 
taxes said sam ponder chief of criminal litigation at the bexar 
county district attorneys office 
but he added the people who are being charged have very 
little in the way of assets that can be seized for the payment of 
taxes most of the dealers charged typically have an apartment and 
car and live from one deal to the next 
