<TEXT>
the worlds richest countries tried hard 
sunday to present a unified front against the threat that the 
persian gulf turmoil could plunge the world into a recession but 
signs of discord emerged from the closeddoor discussions 
finance ministers from britain west germany and france stressed 
the need for vigor in fighting inflation but the united states 
represented by treasury secretary nicholas brady continued to 
press its case that lower interest rates were needed to ward off a 
recession 
the discussions were being held as part of the annual meetings 
of the international monetary fund and the world bank the 
meetings which involve representatives from 152 nations gained 
more urgency this year as finance officials struggled to develop a 
strategy for dealing with the economic fallout from iraqs invasion 
of kuwait 
the finance officials endorsed the broad outlines of a usled 
effort to channel billions of dollars to countries hard hit by the 
persian gulf crisis those include the socalled frontline states 
of turkey egypt and jordan as well as other third world countries 
whose economies have suffered from the loss of markets stemming 
from the un trade embargo against iraq and the world rise in oil 
prices 
however british chancellor of the exchequer john major told 
reporters that decisions regarding specific amounts of assistance 
and how many countries should be helped remained to be worked out 
imf managing director michel camdessus has raised the 
possibility of establishing a voluntary fund with contributions 
coming from the windfall profits made by oilproducing nations 
those funds would be made available to the poorer oilconsuming 
nations officials said potential donor nations were to meet to 
discuss this fund on wednesday 
brady in a speech sunday to the policymaking committee of the 
imf continued to stress the us position that world financial 
leaders needed to be equally worried about inflation and recession 
he said successfully navigating policy to avoid both problems 
will be difficult but it is achievable 
but in their remarks other finance ministers left little doubt 
that they considered inflation to be the greater threat and thus 
would not be moving to lower interest rates 
without preservation of price stability we would lose on all 
fronts west german finance minister theo waigel said 
the clearer we make our antiinflationary determination the 
quicker we will reduce the risks of financial instability said 
french economics minister pierre beregovoy 
while the remarks were made in a closed meeting copies of the 
speeches were made available to reporters 
major who briefed reporters following his address said there 
is nothing to be gained and a great deal to be lost by easing up on 
inflation we have to get it down 
the position of the other countries is likely to make it more 
difficult for the administration to convince the federal reserve of 
the urgency of reducing us interest rates in the face of growing 
signs of economic weakness 
some analysts believe the shock to the us economy from the 
doubling in world oil prices since the aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
will result in a recession in this country beginning before the end 
of the year 
faced with this prospect the administration has been pressuring 
the fed to lower interest rates to spur economic activity however 
analysts said they were not looking for the fed to heed this call 
in view of the fact that interest rates in other countries have 
been rising 
the widening disparity between us and foreign interest rates 
has resulted in foreign investors pulling money out of the us 
market in favor of higher returns overseas if that trend 
accelerated it could trigger a sharp drop in the value of the 
dollar which would only worsen inflationary pressures in the united 
states 
the other finance leaders emphasized the need for the united 
states to do something to get its federal budget under control the 
worlds seven richest countries the united states japan west 
germany britain france canada and italy specifically mentioned 
the us deficit problem in a joint communique issued late 
saturday 
in his speech sunday brady sought to allay fears that the 
current negotiations between congress and the administration will 
fail to craft a credible deficit reduction agreement 
his comments appeared aimed at calls for congress and the 
administration to abandon the grammrudman deficit reduction 
targets because the 50 billion in deficit reduction being 
contemplated for the 1991 budget year would be too great a shock on 
an already weak economy 
