<TEXT>
a special court on sunday ordered ousted 
prime minister benazir bhutto to stand trial next month on charges 
of corruption and misconduct during her 20 months in power 
justice rashid aziz khan issued the notice to bhutto saying the 
armybacked caretaker government had sufficient evidence to support 
its claim he ordered the civil proceedings to start oct 2 
if convicted ms bhutto could be disqualified from the oct 24 
election and barred from politics for up to seven years 
ms bhutto would have the right to appeal to the lahore high 
court and then to the supreme court a process that most likely 
would not be completed before next months ballot 
ms bhutto 37 won election in november 1988 and took office a 
month later as the first woman to lead a modern moslem nation she 
now is a candidate for five seats in the 217member national 
assembly the lawmaking lower house of parliament 
her aides say ms bhutto ran for more than one post in case she 
is disqualified from one seat 
after learning of the judges decision ms bhutto canceled 
appointments and met behind the fortresslike walls of her seaside 
home in karachi about 600 miles southwest of lehore her aides 
refused comment 
ms bhutto previously has called the charges a political 
vendetta and said she would not appear before the special 
onejudge tribunals 
the tribunals were originally set up following the 1977 military 
coup that toppled her father the late prime minister zulfikar ali 
bhutto and resurrected last month by the caretaker government made 
up largely of her opponents and former allies 
if she refuses to appear legal experts say ms bhutto could be 
tried in absentia and held in contempt of court possibly facing a 
fine or arrest 
president ghulam ishaq khan using his constitutional powers 
dismissed ms bhuttos government aug 6 on charges of corruption 
nepotism political incompetence and abuse of power he alleged 
that ms bhuttos government used tens of millions of dollars in 
special funds to buy votes and private business deals charges that 
the former prime minister and her government have denied 
four corruption charges two in lahore and two in karachi 
have been filed against ms bhutto before special tribunals only 
one charge has been accepted hearings are scheduled later this 
week on the others 
the charge accepted by aziz khan alleges ms bhutto misused her 
power by illegally approving the sale of 287 acres of federal land 
to a londonbased company operated by a cousin the land allegedly 
sold at drastically reduced prices was to be used for a luxury 
hotel and resort outside the capital islamabad 
after reviewing the evidence the judge issued a notice ordering 
ms bhutto or her attorney to appear and show why she should not be 
found guilty of misconduct 
shortly after replacing ms bhutto the caretaker government 
began what it called a process of accountability to investigate 
allegations of corruption not only against her former 
administration but against many of her political opponents 
the caretaker government has spent much of the past month trying 
to portray ms bhuttos administration as the most corrupt in 
pakistans 43year history despite allegations the caretaker 
government has yet to make public any proof 
most pakistanis believe the scheme has backfired and evoked 
memories of the same process that ms bhuttos father endured 
before he was hanged by the military government in 1979 
western diplomats have hinted that economic and military aid 
worth hundreds of millions of dollars could be jeopardized if ms 
bhutto is victimized 
most analysts say ms bhutto and her pakistan peoples party 
appear to be gaining strength and could emerge from next months 
election as the single largest party 
