<TEXT>
the swiss in a referendum held against 
the backdrop of the gulf crisis and rising oil prices voted sunday 
against a proposal to close the countrys five nuclear power 
plants 
while narrowly rejecting the socialistbacked plan to 
decommission the plants over the next 30 to 40 years voters 
approved a related constitutional amendment to bar the construction 
of new plants for the next 10 years 
the official results showed 529 percent of the voters opposed 
the total shutdown while 546 percent approved the draft amendment 
barring licensing of new reactors until the year 2000 
seventyone percent approved a third proposal that gives the 
federal government greater power to enact energy saving measures 
the socialist party hailed the vote as a turning point in 
the countrys energy policy it blamed the narrow rejection of the 
shutdown proposal on an expensive publicity campaign by the utility 
industry 
the conservative government which had opposed both measures 
also said it was satisfied with the results it said they showed 
the swiss werent ready to renounce nuclear power yet 
about 40 percent of the eligible voters turned out 
the tenyear moratorium codified the status quo local 
opposition to two major projects has effectively stopped them the 
last nuclear plant went on line in 1984 
protests since 1975 in the basel region frustrated construction 
of a plant at kaiseraugst on the rhine last month another group 
of companies announced it was halting a project at graben near 
bern and planned to sue the federal government to recover 230 
million 
the five operating plants provide 40 percent of switzerlands 
electrical power hydroelectric dams provide the rest 
environmental activists noting that switzerland is a net 
exporter of electricity say increased energy efficiency and 
alternative energies would permit a nuclear shutdown 
in opposing the measures transport and energy minister adolf 
ogi said the persian gulf crisis showed the dangers posed by 
dependency on energy imports 
it was the third time since 1979 that antinuclear groups had 
forced a referendum on atomic power under the swiss system of 
direct democracy any proposal backed by more than 10000 
signatures must be put to a vote 
the move seeking a nuclear shutdown was launched shortly after 
the 1986 chernobyl disaster the government says strict safety 
measures rule out a similar accident at swiss plants 
</TEXT>
